<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FugitiveSurrenders     05-22 0280</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fugitive Surrenders,0288</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Seen on TV Show Gives Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man wanted for investigation of murder in
Ohio and attempted murder in New Jersey flagged down a police car
and surrendered after he was profiled on a national television
show, police said Saturday.
   Stephen Randall Dye, 46, stopped a patrolman about 9:45 p.m.
Friday in downtown San Diego, Sgt. Jim Long said.
   ``He must have seen his face on this nationwide program and
decided to give himself up,'' Long said. ``It all checked out and
he was the guy.''
   New Jersey authorities confirmed Dye's identity, Long said. He
was taken to the San Diego County jail to await extradition.
   Dye was featured on the May 8 episode of ``America's Most
Wanted,'' a Fox Broadcasting Co. show, said executive producer
Michael Linder.
   ``We received over 300 phone calls with tips from viewers. A
number of them placed him in San Diego and Southern California,''
Linder said.
   A county prosecutor's office in New Jersey had asked the show to
profile Dye because an alleged accomplice had been arrested and
authorities wanted to try them together, Linder said.
   The episode depicted an October 1986 incident in which Dye
allegedly shot John Mikrut twice at point-blank range in a house
trailer in Parsippany, N.J., Linder said. Mikrut survived the
attack and participated in the television program.
   The episode also portrayed the May 20, 1981, killing of a
motorcyclist in Cleveland, gave Dye's description and showed
pictures of him, Linder said.
   Linder said 17 people profiled on the program have been
apprehended since the show first aired Feb. 7, 10 of them because
of tips received from television viewers.
</TEXT>
