<1ST_LINE>u a AM-CarolinaOutages 1stLd-Writethru a0733 05-22 0358</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Carolina Outages, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0733,0363</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precede WINSTON-SALEM</HEAD>
<HEAD>Power Outage Cuts Phone Service To Tens Of Thousands</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Recasts throughout with new details. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An electrical failure spurred phone
outages that affected tens of thousands of residents over a
120-mile-wide area for several hours Saturday, making it impossible
for people to make even emergency calls.
   With 911 numbers not operating in the state's largest city,
police here were assigned to fire departments and major
intersections where they could be seen by people who might need
assistance.
   The failure affected an area from Boone, in the state's western
mountains to just west of Rockingham, 120 miles away in the
south-central part of teh state, Southern Bell Telephone Co.
officials said.
   A power failure at a main switching center, unprecedented for
the district, caused a total disruption of long-distance calls and
kept local calls to a trickle, phone company officials said.
   ``As long as anyone remembers, we have not had the main switch
fail. It is a power supply problem,'' said Bob Freedman, the
company's district manager.
   Officials of Duke Power Co., which provides electricity in
Charlotte, could not be reached for comment.
   Freedman said 40 phone company employees were brought in from
around Charlotte to work on the switching problem.
   ``We expect the phones to be working by morning,'' he said. ``We
have more power now than an hour ago.''
   Details of effects of the outage were difficult to obtain
Saturday night, as telephone calls from The Associated Press in
Raleigh to various authorities in 11 counties around Charlotte were
answered with a recording that said calls could not be completed
because circuits were busy.
   The situation caused confusion wherever telephone communications
with the Charlotte area were needed, as with Piedmont Airlines,
which has a hub at the Charlotte airport.
   ``We're not guaranteeing any connections in Charlotte because of
the blackout,'' said Joan Wells, a Piedmont agent at Newark
International Airport in New Jersey Saturday night.
   Charlotte is the largest city in the Carolinas, with about
315,000 people. Its metropolitan area, which borders South
Carolina, has more than a million people.
</TEXT>
