<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Deaths 1stLd-Writethru a0684 05-22 0373</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Deaths, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0684,0383</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS Davis obit; AMs separate moved as a0707, a0659 on Aslan.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Sammy Davis Sr.</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sammy Davis Sr., a vaudeville song-and-dance
man and father of entertainer Sammy Davis Jr. died Saturday, a
publicist said. He was 87.
   Davis died at his Beverly Hills home of natural causes, Arnold
Lipsman said. Sammy Davis Jr. was to deliver the eulogy at public
services Monday at Forest Lawn Memorial Park in Glendale, said Dick
Fisher, a park spokesman.
   The elder Davis was born in Wilmington, N.C., the grandson of
slaves. He began a 40-year career in New York City by winning a
series of dance contests, then joined the Will Maston Trio after
World War I and went on to appear in vaudeville, on stage, and in
posh nightclubs, Lipsman said.
   Davis played Fletcher Henderson in the 1955 film, ``The Benny
Goodman Story'' and appeared on television with such celebrities as
Steve Allen, Eddie Cantor, Milton Berle and Jack Benny, Lipsman
said.
   Davis's last television performance was in 1973 with his son on
a General Electric special, Lipsman said.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Ana Aslan</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ana Aslan, the Romanian scientist who
developed a treatment that held out the vision of restored youth,
has died, Romania's official Agerpres news agency reported
Saturday. She was 91.
   The report monitored in Vienna said Ms. Aslan died Friday in the
Romanian capital of Bucharest. It did not give the cause of death.
   Ms. Aslan was dubbed ``Lady Gerovital'' after the drug she
patented, which was reported to have favorable results in a range
of symptoms, from tightening skin to reactivating brain functions
and repigmentation of hair.
   Despite some skeptics in the medical world, her clients
reportedly included former Chinese leader Mao Tse-tung, former
French president Charles de Gaulle and comedian Charlie Chaplin.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Art Peters</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FREMONT, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Art Peters, who was elected to four
terms and helped bring in $61 million in capital improvements to
this town of 24,000, has died. He was 77.
   City Administrator Jack Sutton, who discovered the body Saturday
morning at Peters' home, said he apparently died in his sleep.
Peters had a history of heart problems and no autopsy was planned,
Sutton said.
</TEXT>
