<2ND_LINE>AM-Car-Train Crash,0214</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Three People Killed In Train-Car Crash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HERRIN, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A car carrying six people to a wedding
smashed into a freight train Saturday, killing three people in the
car, police said.
   The three others in the car, including the driver, were listed
in critical condition Saturday night in hospitals in St. Louis and
Cape Girardeau, Mo., authorities said.
   Officials said the car crashed into the second engine of a
Burlington-Northern freight train at 10:14 a.m. at a railroad
crossing just east of this southern Illinois town.
   The crash occurred at a crossing that has no gates and was the
scene of previous train-car accidents, said Williamson County
Deputy Coroner Bob Wilson.
   Robert Dean Cooper, 38, of De Soto, was pronounced dead at the
scene; two others died later at Herrin Hospital, Wilson said.
   He identified the other victims as Paula R. Henke, 33, and
Melanie Todd, 16, both of Herrin.
   The driver, Tamara Todd, 24, and her 5-year-old daughter, Amanda
R. Missinne, were taken to Southeast Missouri Hospital in Cape
Girardeau, where they were listed in critical condition late
Saturday night, authorities said.
   Ms. Henke's 7-year-old daughter, Jolene Henke, was listed in
critical condition at Cardinal Glennon Hospital in St. Louis,
officials said.
</TEXT>
