<1ST_LINE>u i AM-India-Sikhs 2ndLd-Writethru   05-22 0774</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-India-Sikhs, 2nd Ld - Writethru,a0741,0794</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fifteen Killed Across Punjab; Religious Rites At Golden Temple
Resume</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with four grafs to UPDATE with fatal bomb blast; picks
up 4th pvs: In response...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DEEPAK SHARMA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMRITSAR, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sikh radicals shot and killed 15 people
across the northern Punjab state, and the government flew in
special anti-insurgency forces to combat escalating Sikh violence,
police said Saturday.
   Meanwhile, religious services were held for the first time in
two weeks Sunday at the Golden Temple, Sikhism's most sacred shrine
and the site of a bloody police siege that ended Wednesday.
   Services were led by temple priest Mohan Singh, who had been
released from police detention only a hour before religious rites
began. He was among the high priests arrested during the standoff
at the temple.
   Also Sunday, a bomb believed planted by Sikh extremists exploded
in a crowded railway waiting room in the town of Ludhiana, killing
four people and injuring at least 20, United News of India
reported. Ludhiana is 80 miles southeast of here.
   In response to a wave of Sikh violence that has followed the
siege, contingents of Assam Rifles, a specially trained
anti-guerrilla force, were flown into Punjab on Saturday, state
police chief K.P.S. Gill said.
   ``There is no going back from now on. We are determined to crush
terrorism,'' Gill told a news conference.
   Gill declined to say how many of the troops were brought to
Punjab, where Sikh radicals are waging a guerrilla war for a
separate Sikh nation.
   A committee of Sikh elders that administers the Golden Temple
met for a second day Saturday and agreed to cooperate with the
government to prevent militants from again turning the temple
complex into an armed camp.
   Radical Sikhs occupied the temple for 10 days during a standoff
with Indian police and commandoes who surrounded the complex. The
siege ended Wednesday with the surrender of the last 46 radicals
from the temple complex. At least 40 people died during the
standoff, most of them Sikh militants.
   Shiv Singh Khushipuri, a member of the committee of elders, said
the group decided Saturday it would prohibit anyone from living in
the offices that surround the temple and would insist that weapons
be left outside the complex by visitors. Sikh extremists in the
past have used the offices as hiding places from police.
   Bhan Singh, secretary of the committee, said a compromise
formula was reached after police said they would release some Sikh
priests from prison.
   Four militant Sikh priests were arrested May 12 when they defied
a curfew and tried to march on the occupied shrine.
   Sikh extremists have been waging a guerrilla war since 1982 for
an independent homeland for their minority sect. The Sikhs claim
they are discriminated against by the majority Hindus.
   On Saturday, Sikh gunmen shot and killed nine migrant workers in
Amritsar district and one more in Kapurthala district.
   On Thursday night, Sikh extremists ordered Hindu migrants at a
camp in Amritsar District to line up against a wall and shot five
of them to death and injured several others.
   The latest attack took place early Saturday in the village of
Gujarpura in Amritsar District.
   Chaman Lal, inspector general of the paramilitary Border
Security Force, said a half-dozen extremists opened fire with
Chinese-made AK-47 rifles on the sleeping workers, killing nine and
injuring three others.
   Recent attacks on migrant workers have prompted the exodus of
hundreds of the Hindu laborers who traditionally migrate from the
northern states of Bihar and Orissa to help with planting in
Punjab, India's richest agricultural state. Indian newspapers have
speculated that the Sikh extremists are trying to destroy the
state's economy by undercutting the farmers.
   One migrant laborer was murdered overnight in Punjab's
Karpurthala District to the east of Amritsar.
   In two other attacks in Patiala and Gurdashpur districts, Sikh
gunmen shot and killed four people.
   The latest killings raised to at least 1,141 the number of
people slain by Sikh extremists since the start of the year in
Punjab. Last year, 1,030 people died in terrorist violence.
   The government issued a statewide police alert in Punjab on
Friday and sent 9,000 police and paramilitary troops across the
state to raid hideouts of Sikh extremists.
   More than 200 people have been murdered by suspected Sikh
militants since the police siege of the temple complex began.
   Sikhs, whose religion was founded about 500 years ago as an
alternative to Hinduism and Islam, claim they are discriminated
against by India's majority Hindus.
   Sikhs make up less than 2 percent of India's 800 million people
but are a majority in Punjab.
</TEXT>
