<1ST_LINE>r i BC-Israel     05-22 0494</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Israel,0509</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Three Arabs Die in Occupied Territories</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A car apparently hit by a firebomb burst into
flames Sunday and killed a Palestinian woman and her son. Hospital
officials said another Arab died of a gunshot wound after a
confrontation with Israeli soldiers in the occupied West Bank.
   Three Arab teen-agers were wounded in two separate clashes and
an Israeli man was in intensive care after being burned in a
firebomb attack, the officials and Israel radio said.
   The army confirmed the deaths and said it was investigating the
causes.
   The violence occurred as about 12,000 Palestinian children
returned to schools in east Jerusalem for the first time in more
than three months. Israel closed the schools during the height of
the Arab uprising, which began Dec. 8.
   Sunday's deaths brought to 194 the number of Palestinians who
have died in the anti-occupation unrest, according to U.N. figures.
Two Israelis have also been killed.
   Shamseh Al Kadah, 65, and her son Mohammed Salah Ghanem, 36, of
the village of Shuweika, died when their car caught fire in the
West Bank town of Tulkarem as they drove from Tulkarem Hospital
where Ghanem's wife was giving birth, hospital officials said.
   An official at Israel's Pathological Institute, Abu Kabir, said
the two apparently died in a firebombing attack.
   Arab witnesses said the fire occurred after soldiers fired
warning shots toward the car, which was traveling through a closed
military zone.
   Kawther Miri, 23, of a refugee camp near Tulkarem, died of a
bullet wound to the chest suffered during clashes with soldiers
Saturday, said an official at Rafidiyeh Hospital in Nablus where
she was treated.
   Also Sunday, hundreds of protesters in Nablus hurled rocks at
soldiers on an avenue named for slain Palestine Liberation
Organization military commander Khalil Wazir, hospital officials
said. Israel has been blamed for the April 16 slaying.
   Two 19-year-old youths were wounded by bullets in the legs and
three were treated for beating injuries, said officials at Nablus'
Al Ittihad Hospital.
   In the occupied Gaza Strip, soldiers clashed Saturday night with
protesters at the Deir El Balah refugee camp, wounding an
18-year-old youth in the right leg, officials at Gaza City's Ahli
Arab Hospital said.
   Yaacov Askayo of Jerusalem was being treated Sunday in an
intensive care unit for severe burns suffered after his vehicle was
hit by a firebomb in the West Bank city of Jericho, Israel radio
said.
   But the wave of unrest apparently died down in the
Israeli-annexed quarters of Jerusalem, and Israeli officials
reopened schools on Sunday.
   Israel reopened 31 kindergarten, elementary and high schools in
east Jerusalem and the radio said about 80 percent of a student
body of 16,000 showed up for classes. Pupils will have to attend an
extra hour of classes daily and give up part of their summer
vacations to make up for the lost time.
   But private schools, which closed themselves at about the same
time, did not reopen.
</TEXT>
