<FILEID>AP-NR-05-22-88 1212EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Reagan-Anti-Communism Bjt   05-22 0996</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Anti-Communism, Bjt,950</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan's Anti-Communist Rhetoric Dates Back Nearly Four Decades</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The confrontational tone of President Reagan's
pre-summit rhetoric apparently came as a surprise to Soviet leader
Mikhail S. Gorbachev, even though the president has been using
similar anti-communist rhetoric for nearly four decades.
   Reagan takes to Moscow the view that the relationship between
the United States and the Soviet Union, no matter how gentlemanly
it becomes, is a conflict between good and evil.
   ``He is probably facing realities, what appear to him realities
now, but his likes and dislikes are probably the same as they were
all along,'' says Vladimir Petrov, professor emeritus of
international affairs at George Washington University.
   Gorbachev reacted with dismay after the president made a world
affairs council speech in Springfield, Mass., on April 21 boasting
that his has been the administration that ``said communism was
bad.''
   He's been saying that, however, ever since his days as a movie
actor.
   In 1951, testifying at a House Committee on Un-American
Activities hearing on alleged communist influence in Hollywood,
Reagan said, ``I abhor their philosophy, but I detest their tactics
which are those of a fifth column and are dishonest.''
   That was when he was still a Democrat. After he became a
Republican, he was more outspoken.
   In 1981, in his first news conference as president, Reagan said,
``The only morality they recognize is what will further their
cause, meaning they reserve unto themselves the right to commit any
crime, to lie, to cheat in order to attain that.''
   The next year, in a speech to members of the British Parliament
in London, the president spoke of ``a march of freedom and
democracy which will leave Marxism-Leninism on the ash heap of
history.''
   In a speech in Orlando, Fla., in March, 1983, during the
national debate on the nuclear weapons freeze movement, he
cautioned members of the evangelical clergy against being tempted
to ``label both sides equally at fault, to ignore the facts of
history and the aggressive impulses of an evil empire, to simply
call the arms race a giant misunderstanding and thereby remove
yourself from the struggle between right and wrong and good and
evil.''
   In Springfield, Reagan returned to the same theme, saying of his
administration, ``We acknowledged the depth of our disagreements
and their fundamental, moral import. In this way, we acknowledged
that the differences that separated us and the Soviets were deeper
and wider than just missile counts and numbers of warheads.''
   He also said that by ``making a moral and spiritual point'' of
East-West differences, his administration had steered U.S.-Soviet
relations toward ``a period of realistic engagement.''
   In that spirit, he accused the Soviets of backing regimes that
were ``an outrage to the conscience of mankind'' and said that if
the Soviet Union was changing it was ``because the costs of
aggression and the real moral difference between our systems were
brought home to it.''
   Gorbachev, decrying this ``confrontational'' approach, said,
``We have so far been showing restraint, but if we reciprocate _
and we can do so over a very wide range of issues _ the atmosphere
of Soviet-American relations can become such that it will make it
no longer possible to solve any further issues.''
   The Soviet leader appeared to lament a departure from the
atmosphere of cordiality that prevailed at his summit meeting with
Reagan in Washington in December.
   During a break in that meeting, the president told a group of
columnists that Gorbachev, unlike past Soviet leaders, had not
``openly expressed ... acceptance of the Marxian theory of the
one-world communist state'' and that he seemed to believe in
``competitive societies ... living in peace in the world together.''
   Reagan also said, however, ``I haven't softened up ... this
doesn't mean that I'm dropping my guard or anything.''
   ``It's a very odd situation,'' said Michael R. Beschloss, an
adjunct historian at the Smithsonian Institution and author of a
recent book that describes the abortive Eisenhower-Khruschev summit
of 1960 _ the last time a Republican president winding up two full
terms in office went to see a Soviet leader.
   ``On the one hand, he (Reagan) has been very bitter in his
estimate of what motivates the Soviet Union, and if he were still
to believe that, it would conflict with what he has been doing over
the past year. He has tried to paper that over by saying that
Gorbachev is a new type of Soviet leader. That has got him in great
trouble with conservatives.''
   In the view of some experts, Gorbachev may be in a similar
situation at home.
   ``Quite possibly there are also people around him in Moscow who
don't like the many concessions he has made to the United States,
and he has to stand up in order to demonstrate to his associates
that he is no pushover,'' said Petrov.
   ``Maybe Gorbachev doesn't think he has been adequately rewarded
by the United States for his being so forthcoming, that we keep on
growling even if he delivered more than his predecessors ever could
or would.''
   There probably will be more smiles than growls in the public
meetings in Moscow, but not because Ronald Reagan has changed his
views.
   ``I wasn't up on the communists,'' he once said in looking back
on his days with the Screen Actors Guild. He has had some 40 years
to bone up on them, and his lesson is still, as he put in a 1985
speech to the United Nations:
   ``We Americans do not accept that any government has the right
to command and order the lives of its people, that any nation has
an historic right to use force to export its ideology. This belief
regarding the nature of man and the limitations of government is at
the core of our deep and abiding differences with the Soviet Union,
differences that put us into natural conflict _ and competition _
with one another.''
</TEXT>
