<1ST_LINE>r w AM-TogoAmbassador     05-22 0577</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Togo Ambassador,540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>From Texas to Togo: A Ninth Grader Reaches His Goal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rush Walker Taylor Jr. doesn't remember making
a speech in ninth grade about wanting to be an ambassador. But at
least one of his classmates in Crockett, Texas, four decades later,
remembers.
   And when word from Washington reached Crockett that Taylor was
on his way to West Africa as envoy to Togo _ a ribbon of savanna,
hills and coastal plains _ the classmate reminded the career
diplomat in a letter of those dreams so long ago, born in the piney
woods of East Texas.
   Taylor's father, a clothing company salesman whose territory
covered a big chunk of East Texas, moved his family from Arkansas
to Crockett, which now has about 7,500 inhabitants, when Rush Jr.
was 8.
   They settled into a house built in 1830, where Davy Crockett
spent the night on his way to the Alamo, and it was there in one of
the earliest cities in Texas that Taylor decided to become an
ambassador.
   A teacher who had traveled in Europe kindled his interest in
history and the world, and by the time he was in high school,
Taylor was determined to work for the foreign service. He began his
career with the State Department in 1962, after graduating from
Harvard and the University of Virginia law school and serving in
the U.S. Army for two years.
   President Reagan in April nominated Taylor to be ambassador to
Togo, a sliver of country smaller than West Virginia that the State
Department says is one of the world's least developed. It has a per
capita income of $250.
   Taylor is to be sworn in on Thursday and when he leaves for the
capital, Lome, in June, Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, says Taylor will
be taking a knowledge of the United States molded by life in
small-town America.
   ``I think it's helpful, when you've got people around the world
representing America who are from smaller towns and who understand
the fundamental values of America. If you're going to represent
American interests you have to know what they are,'' said Gramm.
``You can't grow up in Crockett and not understand America.''
   ``He combines the best in rural roots, good education, small
town boy makes good, in an area that has until pretty recently been
dominated by people who were primarily very high income people,''
said Gramm, who introduced Taylor to the Senate Foreign Relations
Committee when it considered the nomination.
   Since word first got out, Taylor said he's received more than a
dozen phone calls and letters of congratulations from people in
Crockett who he had not see since school.
   ``One guy reminded me of when we were in ninth grade, when I
made some kind of speech about wanting to be an ambassador. I had
forgotten, but he had not,'' he said.
   Taylor, 53, who will be serving in his first ambassadorial post,
has had other African assignments, in Yaounde, Cameroon, in the
early 1960s, and in Guinea-Bissau. He also has worked in
Washington, Rome, Florence, Portugal and the Bahamas.
   He said the United States ``couldn't ask for better relations
with the government of Togo,'' although U.S. efforts are dwarfed by
the contributions of France.
   Togo has an open, commercially oriented economy with a liberal
investment code, the State Department said. It is a predominately
agricultural country, and exports phosphates, cotton, coffee and
cocoa.
</TEXT>
