<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Pena,0331</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Denver Mayor Weds Law School Graduate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Denver Mayor Federico Pena and law
school graduate Ellen Hart were wed this weekend in a Catholic
ceremony at the University of New Mexico campus.
   The marriage is the first for both Hart, 30, and the 41-year-old
Pena, who is Denver's first Hispanic mayor.
   Saturday's wedding capped a year of triumph for Pena, whose
political career nearly came to a halt last year. He finished
second to political newcomer Don Bain in last year's re-election
primary before narrowly defeating Bain in the runoff.
   Then, this year, the Democratic mayor survived a recall attempt
by ex-city workers and others who accused him of fiscal
irresponsibility and were unhappy with the cleanup from a December
snowstorm.
   In March, things began turning around for Pena, with the signing
of contracts for construction of a convention center and the
ground-breaking last month.
   And last week, in a major victory for the mayor, voters approved
a plan to annex 45 square miles of Adams County for a new $3
billion airport for Denver.
   In a sun-drenched garden prior to the ceremony, Pena said, ``We
were worried about the rain, but everybody prayed extra hard and
it's beautiful.'' Pena said the couple would honeymoon for 10 days
in Spain.
   ``We haven't had a chance to take much time off,'' he said.
``It's been a hectic week.
   The groom had been considered one of Denver's most eligible
bachelors until his engagement to Hart.
   The bride, an avid distance runner, met Pena four years ago at
the Mayor's Cup 10-mile race in Denver.
   A fine arts graduate of Harvard University, she graduated this
month from the University of Colorado School of Law in Boulder,
Colo. Her father is former dean of the University of New Mexico Law
School.
   She said she hopes to work in family law, American Indian law
and possibly sports law.
