<FILEID>AP-NR-05-22-88 1235EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Hastings-Impeach Bjt   05-22 0716</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hastings-Impeach, Bjt,690</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Panel Moving Cautiously in Impeachment Proceedings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT M. ANDREWS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A dark cloud of controversy hangs over House
impeachment proceedings against federal judge Alcee L. Hastings of
Miami, giving some members of the Judiciary Committee's
investigative panel an uncomfortable case of election-year jitters.
   The panel is moving reluctantly and with great caution for two
reasons. One concerns the possibility of setting a historic
precedent. The other is the question whether in 1988, when a black
man is running for president, America is truly colorblind.
   The House has impeached 11 federal judges for ``high crimes and
misdemeanors'' in its 200-year history. Only five of them were
subsequently convicted by the Senate and removed from office.
   But never has a federal judge been impeached after being
acquitted of criminal charges, according to the Senate historians.
If impeached, Hastings would be the first.
   His case also is unprecedented because Hastings, unlike all the
other judges, is black.
   The racial issue clearly troubles Rep. John Conyers Jr.,
D-Mich., chairman of the House Judiciary subcommittee on criminal
justice, which will resume its impeachment hearings on Tuesday.
   Conyers, who also is black, complained at the very start of the
hearings last week that the Hastings case was ``exceedingly
difficult and trying,'' partly because of suggestions that the
charges against Florida's first black federal judge were racially
and politically motivated.
   Other panel members seemed equally distressed. Liberal Rep. Don
Edwards, D-Calif., called it an ``unwelcome'' duty. Rep. Hamilton
Fish, R-N.Y., said, ``It is not a pleasant responsibility to judge
a federal judge.''
   ``Frankly I don't want to be here this morning,'' said Rep. Mike
Synar, D-Okla., ``and I'm sure the judge doesn't either.''
   In an emotional opening statement delivered under oath, Hastings
intensified the panel's discomfort by reminding them that a trial
jury had acquitted him five years ago of conspiring to solicit a
$150,000 bribe from two convicted racketeers.
   ``I am not guilty, but I am not free,'' Hastings shouted,
demanding that his judges in the House ``set me free.''
   The subcommittee is looking into charges by a special five-judge
panel of the 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals that Hastings
actually committed the crime and tried to conceal his part in the
bribery scheme by lying under oath and fabricating evidence at his
trial. The panel investigated the case for 3{ years.
   Conyers resurrected the racial issue when John Doar, chief
counsel for the appellate panel, outlined the massive evidence he
had uncovered _ some of it unavailable to the Miami trial jury _ to
support the subcommittee's charges of impeachable misconduct by
Hastings.
   Conyers repeatedly asked Doar whether overt or even
``subconscious racism'' played any part in Hastings' prosecution or
the subsequent investigation by his fellow judges.
   ``Absolutely not,'' replied Doar, the respected former assistant
U.S. attorney general in charge of the Justice Department's civil
rights division during the Johnson administration.
   Rep. George Gekas, R-Pa., declared there had ``never been a
hint'' that any part of the House panel's own year-long inquiry had
been racially motivated.
   Conyers also evoked the specter of political intrigue when he
charged that the federal judiciary had become ``conservatized and
in some instances politicized'' under the Reagan administration.
   Though prosecutors failed to make their case against Hastings,
they did against his alleged co-conspirator, Washington lawyer
William A. Borders, who was convicted in 1982 of arranging the
bribe and was sentenced to five years in prison.
   Terence Anderson of Miami, Hastings' chief counsel, said
prosecutors also succeeded in their aim of forcing Hastings, after
Borders' arrest, to remove himself from presiding over two major
court cases in Miami involving organized crime figures and Haitian
refugees, both of high-level interest in the Justice Department.
   The political motivation behind Hastings' prosecution, Anderson
said, ``is a lingering issue that they (the House panel) are not
looking at, and won't if they can avoid it.''
   Justice Department spokesman John Russell refused comment on
Anderson's allegation.
   The House subcommittee has subpoened Borders in the hope of
obtaining his crucial testimony, especially about whether Hastings
was ever aware that his close friend was arranging a bribe for him.
   Borders has refused to testify against Hastings at either of
their separate trials, nor did he ever appear before the judicial
investigative panel.
</TEXT>
