<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Australia-Koalas     05-22 0213</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Australia-Koalas,0220</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Koalas May Be Extinct In 10 Years Without Research, Expert Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SYDNEY, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Urban expansion and a terminal disease
could wipe out Australia's koala bears within 10 years, a leading
veterinarian said Sunday.
   Dr. Steve Brown, director of the World Koala Research Corp.,
said $3.5 million in research money was needed to help save the
marsupials from extinction.
   Half of Australia's 200,000 to 400,000 koalas are suffering from
chlamydia, a sexually transmitted disease that causes blindness and
infertility, Brown said at a news conference.
   About 80 percent of their natural habitat has been destroyed,
and more is planned for conversion to farmland, he said.
   Brown said little is known about the biology, ecology and health
of koalas because little research has been done on them.
   Scientists don't even know what constitutes an ideal environment
for koalas or how many species of leaves they eat, he said.
   ``Scientists have the laboratories, the expertise and the staff
to solve these questions, but no money,'' he said.
   ``Australians are so apathetic about their unique animals they
don't even know they have already lost 17 native mammal species. I
don't think they even know there's 25 on an endangered list,'' he
said. ``We have plundered this country, its animals and its
environment.''
</TEXT>
