<1ST_LINE>r i AM-China-Storm     05-22 0204</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-Storm,0214</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rainstorm Kills 60, Injures 162</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FUZHOU, China (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 60 people died in a rainstorm
that raged for 21 hours in the southern coastal province of Fujian,
a provincial official said Sunday.
   The official Xinhua News Agency reported that 162 were injured
in the storm, which started Friday at 7 p.m. and lasted until 4
p.m. Saturday.
   Three hundred homes were destroyed, 120 bridges washed out and
1,976 acres of rice fields were flooded, the report said.
   Fujian Deputy Governor Yu Dexin said Governor Wang Zhaoguo was
at the scene leading rescue operations and that land transportation
to the province's northern county of Jiangyang had been halted.
   Rainfall near the town of Wufu in Jianyang county reached 12.16
inches, making all roads impassable, the agency said.
   The storm was the latest bad weather that has plagued China this
spring.
   Hailstorms swept through the central and coastal provinces
earlier this month, killing at least 24 people and injuring more
than 250.
   A tornado in southern China's Guangdong province killed five
people in early May.
   Also this month, parts of northern and central China were hit by
heavy rains after severe droughts that in some places lasted more
than 20 months.
