<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Gulf-Bluegrass     05-22 0465</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf-Bluegrass,0485</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nashville Group Brings Down-home Music to Persian Gulf</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENDA SMILEY</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The turbaned teen-agers in the back rows
clapped with the beat. Their heads, bodies and sandaled feet moved
energetically to the American music that few, if any, ever had
heard before.
   The down-home sounds of the Nashville Bluegrass Band were an
unusual experience for the blind Arab students, special guests at a
benefit concert for Bahrain's Al Noor Institute for the Blind.
   In performances Thursday through Sunday, the five-member group
introduced an eclectic form of Americana to a new Middle East
audience as part of a cultural exchange program sponsored by the
U.S. Information Service.
   ``The lyrical content may not get across, but the rhythms and
beats, and what's going on up on stage with the musicians, will be
picked up and enjoyed by the people,'' said banjo player Alan
O'Bryant.
   O'Bryant, of Reidsville, N.C., believes music works as an
ambassadorial tool because it ``can communicate with people in ways
mere words cannot.''
   At a Friday evening show at a local amusement park, Bahraini men
in ankle-length robes, or dishdashas, broke into traditional Arab
dancing that went on until dark, when ``we couldn't even see our
instruments any more,'' said guitarist and lead singer Pat Enright,
of Huntington, Ind.
   ``Everybody was trying to outdo everybody else. One guy walked
into the circle, did a complete back flip and walked out again. It
was definitely the highlight of our visit,'' he said.
   Although many Arabs prefer traditional music, Western music is
popular among the young.
   The audience is more limited for such specialized music as
bluegrass, whose deep roots are said to lie in music taken to
America by Scottish and Irish immigrants.
   A U.S. Embassy official, speaking on condition of anonymity,
said bluegrass was chosen for this year's U.S.-sponsored ``Arts
America'' program so people could experience music that ``shows the
depth and breadth of America.''
   Last year's program in the Middle East featured break dancing.
   A handful of other country-bluegrass bands have visited the
region in the past decade but appeared mostly at hotels catering to
foreigners.
   U.S. embassies work with government officials to make sure
performers and material are suitable for local audiences.
   In Islamic countries, there's no place for gospel music with
strong religious themes. In some, such as Saudi Arabia, males and
females do not appear together.
   The all-male Nashville band, which also includes mandolin player
Mike Compton, fiddler Stuart Duncan and bassist Mark Hembree, also
scheduled stops in Qatar, Bangladesh, Pakistan, Iraq and Egypt.
   But it may take a few more tours before ``My Native Home'' finds
a home on Arab radio station playlists.
   ``Yes, I've heard this music before,'' a youth at the amusement
park told a reporter. ``It's from Hawaii, no?''
</TEXT>
