<HEAD>Bright & Brief</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Maass is cq in first item</NOTE>
<DATELINE>AMES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Commencement exercises at Iowa State
University were anything but ordinary for Julie Quinn.
   Paul Maass, senior class president, was making the traditional
announcement of the class gift to the university Saturday when he
made another announcement _ a proposal of marriage to Ms. Quinn.
   ``It definitely shocked the whole crowd,'' said Maass, 22, a
graduate in agricultural economics from Paullina.
   Ames' Hilton Coliseum was nearly packed, ``and the first thing I
heard was this sigh across the crowd,'' he said. ``I said, `Please
stand and wave if you'll marry me.'''
   Ms. Quinn, 22, an Iowa City native who has two more years of
studying special education, was sitting in the audience and heard
the marriage proposal but didn't hear the part about standing.
   ``Then I figured it out and I waved my hand and shook my head
yes. ... I waved hard,'' Ms. Quinn said. ``I just saw everybody
staring at me.''
   Ms. Quinn now must decide if she's going to finish at Iowa State
or move to Omaha, Neb., where Maass has landed a job.
   ``We don't know. We haven't had time to talk about this at
all,'' she said. ``I was 100 percent shocked.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BOISE, Idaho (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Working as if someone had punched their
fast-forward button, framers, electricians, painters, roofers and
other builders put up a house in less than nine hours.
   More than 400 people, including suppliers, helped build the
single-story, three-bedroom, two-bathroom house in eight hours and
54 minutes Saturday to kick off the Boise Parade of Homes.
   A gunshot at 8 a.m. gave the signal for members of the Building
Contractors Association of Southwest Idaho to start.
   Since the cement foundation had been installed earlier in the
week, the framers went to work like they were at an old-fashioned
barn-raising, hoisting wooden walls.
   Spectators had their own viewing stand across the street. They
were able to tell who was who by workers' color-coded T-shirts.
Framers sported fuchsia; electricians, lime green.
   One spectator, Marion Stevenson of Boise, said the coordination
of the workers astounded him.
   ``I only saw one worker just about get hit,'' Stevenson said.
   Also watching the process were the buyers of the house _ Brad
Chapple and his fiancee, Leslie Cozza, who plan to move in June 6.
They paid $68,000 for the house.
   Chapple said they were getting a 10-year warranty with the home,
instead of the usual one-year warranty.
   Chapple admitted he was a nervous first-time homeowner. ``It's
been a heavy stress factor,'' he said of the planning and
coordination.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Tennessee Legislature has quietly
reeled in two more official state creatures.
   Without the ado that might muddy the water, the lawmakers have
approved resolutions so far in 1988 to name the catfish as the
official Tennessee Commercial Fish and the largemouth bass as the
official Tennessee Game Fish.
   They join the passion flower as the state wildflower, the iris
as its cultivated flower, the mockingbird as the official bird, the
tulip poplar as the state tree, and the raccoon as Tennessee's wild
animal.
   There's also the firefly and the lady bug, which jointly reign
as the state's insects thanks to a political compromise. And
perhaps thinking of their own words, lawmakers designated the pearl
as the state gem.
   Two separate legislative sessions designated pet rocks _ in
1969, agate got the nod, but in 1979, it was limestone.
   But there's still no state vegetable: a 1979 proposal to give
the honor to corn was killed by a heavily Democratic Agriculture
Committee with the explanation that corn is a legume, not a
vegetable, according to its sponsor, former Republican House member
Dale Kelley.
