<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Moynihan     05-22 0650</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Moynihan,0670</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Republicans Lack Name Candidate To Battle Moynihan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARC HUMBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, who
plans to announce Monday that he'll seek a third term, has
Republican leaders worried that he could win by a large enough
margin to damage GOP chances of carrying the state in the
presidential race.
   At the moment, the likely Republican challenger for the two-term
senator is Robert McMillan, a little-known Long Island lawyer.
   ``This, at best, is going to be a tough state for (Vice
President George) Bush and the few percentage points that Moynihan
might skew the election or that (Republican Robert) McMillan might
skew the election are important enough for them to go after,'' said
Buffalo's Victor Farley, the Erie County GOP chairman.
   ``I don't know that it'll be a major factor, but it'll have an
impact,'' said Richard Rosenbaum, a former state chairman and a
Republican national committeeman, of the possible effect of the
Senate race on the presidential contest in New York.
   John Marino, executive director of the state Democratic
Committee and a political operative of Gov. Mario Cuomo, calls the
Moynihan situation a ``reverse coattail effect.''
   ``In a close race at the top, it'll make a difference if
Moynihan can win by a two-to-one margin and that's why Jonathan
Bush got involved in trying to find an opponent,'' said Marino.
   Jonathan Bush, the vice president's brother and a top Republican
fund-raiser in New York, has been encouraging McMillan, 55, to run.
McMillan is expected to announce his candidacy early next month.
   What has Republicans worried is that without a strong challenge
to Moynihan, some potential GOP voters may simply stay home in
November and thus deny Bush needed votes in a close race.
   Initially, Republicans had expected to have a celebrity
candidate. There was speculation that former U.S. Secretary of
State Henry Kissinger might be interested. He wasn't. Rudolph
Giuliani, the New York City-based federal prosecutor who had made a
name for himself convicting Mafia chieftains and corrupt
politicians, kept Republican leaders hanging for months before
finally bowing out earlier this year.
   ``I think he's vulnerable,'' Rep. Jack Kemp, R-N.Y., said of
Moynihan, ``but there's no one in the Giuliani or Kissinger class''
to run.
   Kemp, after his bid for the GOP presidential nomination
collapsed this spring, was mentioned as a possible Moynihan
opponent.
   ``I thought it was too late for me to shift gears,'' Kemp said
of his decision not to run.
   State Comptroller Edward Regan, a proven strong draw for
Republicans, said he viewed the U.S. Senate as ``a demotion'' when
he declined.
   Former U.S. Ambassador to Austria Ronald Lauder, son of
cosmetics magnate Estee Lauder, said he wanted to spend time with
his family.
   Farley said some of the potential big-name candidates were
scared off by the money needed for the race and Moynihan's apparent
strength with the New York electorate.
   ``Big names have big egos,'' said Farley. ``Big egos don't want
to be deflated. And since they don't want to be deflated, they're
looking for a sure thing. So you only get someone who wants to move
up.''
   ``You give me a weak incumbent and you'll find plenty of
Republicans,'' Cuomo said.
   Of those New Yorkers polled in January by the Marist College
Institute for Public Opinion, more than 57 percent said Moynihan
had done a good or excellent job and 45 percent said they
``definitely plan to vote for him.''
   Already, Moynihan has raised more than $3.6 million for his
re-election campaign and spent about $2 million. He's expected to
easily raise several million more.
   Republican leaders are assuring McMillan they can raise the $3
million he said he needs for the race, but the GOP has had
difficulty in raising big money for candidates since the late Gov.
Nelson Rockefeller left office in late 1973 to become vice
president under Gerald Ford.
</TEXT>
