<FILEID>AP-NR-05-22-88 1342EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-GulfRdp     05-22 0577</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf Rdp,0593</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iran Conducting Big Naval Maneuvers in Gulf</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD PYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran said Sunday it was carrying out
major military maneuvers involving warplanes and more than 50 ships
in the Persian Gulf and waters just outside.
   Tehran radio, monitored by the British Broadcasting Corp., said
``helicopters, air force fighter planes and the airborne brigade of
the army'' also were participating in the exercises.
   The report appeared to indicate that virtually all of Iran's
biggest naval vessels were involved in the exercises _ codenamed
``Zolfaqar'' _ in the Persian Gulf, Gulf of Oman and Indian Ocean.
   The radio quoted a Capt. Shirazi, whom it identified as ``naval
commander in Chabahar,'' as saying in an interview that
``missile-carrying destroyers, heavy destroyers, missile-launching
frigates and personnel carriers would be taking part in the
maneuvers.''
   The Iranians lost six naval vessels in a major clash with the
U.S. Navy on April 18.
   Iran announced more than a week ago that it was planning to
stage naval exercises in the Strait of Hormuz, the gateway to the
gulf, to show that it remained a major power in the area.
   Gulf shipping officials and U.S. intelligence sources at the
Pentagon in Washington recently reported an increase in the numbers
and activities of Iran's fleet of small armed speedboats around the
Bandar Abbas naval base in the Strait of Hormuz.
   Since the battle with U.S. forces, Iranian Revolutionary Guards
have carried out three known speedboat attacks on neutral ships in
the strait _ one on April 24 and two last week.
   Iranian patrol boats also have been intercepting vessels passing
through the Hormuz strait to check for cargoes bound for Iraq, its
foe in a nearly 8-year-old war.
   A war communique quoted by the official Islamic Republic News
Agency did not mention naval maneuvers but said Iranian air force
planes flew ``routine patrol missions'' over the Persian Gulf and
Gulf of Oman ``in support of the navy, reconnoitering 21 vessels in
the waterway.''
   In the April 18 fighting, the 1,540-ton frigate Sahand was sunk
and a sister ship, the Sabalan, was disabled. Other losses included
a Kaman-class patrol boat, sunk after it fired a missile at a U.S.
warship and missed, and three speedboats.
   Iran said 44 of its men were killed in the clashes, triggered by
U.S. attacks that destroyed two Iranian oil platforms in the south
central gulf. The United States said those attacks were in reprisal
for Iranian mining of gulf waters.
   U.S. officials say that despite the setbacks, Iran remains a
potent naval force whose threats of revenge for the April 18 losses
cannot be taken lightly.
   Adm. William J. Crowe, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff,
said during a military awards ceremony May 5 that the Iranians
``have a considerable capability and they have standoff missile
capability, which we are always concerned about.''
   H2an's navy includes two former U.S. destroyers, a British
destroyer and two corvettes _ all of World War II vintage _ and
three supply ships, two of which are sometimes used for naval
patrol operations in the southern gulf.
   The destroyers and corvettes have not been sighted in recent
months and their operational status is unclear, U.S. officers say.
   Iran also has 10 fast-attack patrol craft like the one sunk on
April 18 and perhaps 100 speedboats equipped with a variety of
weapons including recoilless rifles, anti-aircraft guns, heavy
machine guns and rocket-propelled grenade launchers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
