<DOCNO> AP880522-0029 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-22-88 1409EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Dukakis-Style Bjt   05-22 0766</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis-Style, Bjt,730</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Doesn't Exude Excitement, But Has His Own Style</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   While most politicians crave seeing their
faces on the television news or reading their names in newspapers,
Michael Dukakis often acts indifferent to that aspect of
campaigning.
   As the Democratic presidential front-runner campaigned through
critically important California, he repeatedly passed up easy
chances to add to George Bush's discomfort over the
administration's handling of Panamanian military leader Manuel
Antonio Noriega.
   ``I'm going to do everything I can to stay positive,'' he said
when asked on his campaign plane why he had avoided direct
criticism of the man certain to be his Republican opponent in the
fall.
   Dukakis' fierce determination to do it his way distinguishes his
campaign from those of any other presidential candidates _ this or
any other campaign year.
   And while the Dukakis style may seem odd to observers accustomed
to traditional campaigns, no one can argue with its success.
   In just over two weeks, when the last four Democratic primaries
are held June 7, Dukakis is certain to collect enough delegates to
give him more than the 2,081 needed to clinch his party's
presidential nomination.
   As the primary season progressed, Dukakis often was criticized
as dull and passionless, a speaker with all the impact of sodium
pentathol.
   But out of the initially large Democratic field, only Jesse
Jackson remains to challenge him.
   One thing the Massachusetts governor may have in common with a
select number of past presidential candidates is the ability to
represent what many voters are looking for.
   In 1960, John F. Kennedy excited voters because he represented
generational change. In 1976, Jimmy Carter campaigned as an
outsider in a year voters were fed up with the Washington insiders
who'd brought them Vietnam and Watergate.
   Dukakis exudes hands-on competence at a time when opinion polls
suggest Americans are looking for a change from the hands-off style
of President Reagan.
   Sometimes Dukakis goes out of his way to stay out of sight of
the media.
   ``He runs around closing events that we scheduled as open,''
said campaign adviser Anthony Podesta.
   The candidate often speaks at schools and when he does he meets
privately before his speech with a group of students.
   He said he started doing that a few years ago when he became
concerned about the extent of drug and alcohol abuse in schools.
   ``I'd go into a school and people would say we've got a great
program,'' he said.
   ``I finally said, look, before I do these assemblies, I'd like
to meet with a cross-section of the kids, 25 or 30, just me, no
adults, no teachers.''
   At those sessions, he said, he got a much more accurate picture
of what was happening in the schools.
   Would he continue holding such meetings as president?
   ``I expect to,'' he said.
   Dukakis attacks the administration for its handling of the
Noriega affair, while avoiding direct personal attacks.
   With the tone of an outraged manager, Dukakis demanded ``an
explanation'' of why the administration was ``doing business with
Noriega.''
   ``We won't be doing business with drug-peddling Panamanian
dictators,'' is a stock line in the Dukakis stump speech.
   But when he was asked to comment on the latest reports of a
pending deal that would have Noriega relinquish power in exchange
for the United States dropping drug charges against him, Dukakis
would only say, ``I don't know anything about it.''
   When asked about reports that Bush was separating himself from
Reagan on the question of negotiations with Noriega, Dukakis
refused to take a shot at the vice president.
   Talking later about his determination to wage a positive
campaign, he said, ``The Bush campaign went negative for three
weeks and all it did was hurt them.''
   He is convinced that ``the American peoplke are fed up with
that. They don't want to know what he thinks of me or I think of
him.
   ``They want to know which one of us has the stuff to do this job
and what we're for and that's what I'm going to do.''
   But Dukakis also passes up one of the most time-tested ways
candidates get across to voters what they stand for and what they
would do as president.
   One of the most common occurences on the campaign of a
challenger to an incumbent administration is for that candidate to
approach reporters, often the first thing in the morning, and offer
his views on the biggest news of the day.
   But not on the Dukakis campaign. Rarely does he vary from his
carefully structured appearances.
</TEXT>
