<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People     05-22 0832</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People,0861</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>People in The News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STANLEY, Idaho (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Singer-songwriter Carole King says timber
companies are asking for a kind of welfare and she doesn't want to
see them get it.
   King, also a wilderness advocate, says timber companies want to
harvest more trees in Idaho but need the U.S. Forest Service to
build roads, at taxpayers' expense, to get to them.
   The cost of building the roads in many cases is greater than the
money the Forest Service collects for the trees, King told about
100 people attending the Idaho Conservation League annual meeting
Friday. She also sang a few songs, accompanying herself on the
guitar.
   While she urges setting aside land for the public, King had her
own tussle with the Forest Service and Custer County over access to
property in the county, where she lives.
   When she bought Robinson Bar Ranch, she locked a gate on a road
through her property and contended that her rights were violated
when the county declared the road public. The Forest Service
claimed the closure blocked public access to public lands.
   The Idaho Supreme Court ruled Feb. 10 that the property belongs
to King and her husband, Rick Sorensen, and there is no public
access involved.
   ``I protected my rights and now I am working to protect
everyone's rights,'' King said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LINCOLN, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Willie Nelson says he never wanted to get
involved with politics prior to his involvement in the first Farm
Aid concert.
   The country music star thought he was playing ``just another
charity show'' when he helped Neil Young and John Mellencamp
organize the benefit performance on behalf of financially strapped
farmers.
   Instead, Farm Aid has become a 4-year-old effort that has led
Nelson to become politically active and has required that he spend
much more time than he anticipated trying to help the family farmer.
   ``I'll be honest with you. I never really wanted to get involved
with politics. I always felt that was something the other guy
should do and I should sit on the side and criticize,'' Nelson
said. ``But when I got into Farm Aid and into the farm situation,
it wasn't possible for me to say `I don't want to do anything'
anymore.''
   For the past three years, Nelson has rounded up his friends to
play a giant concert to benefit family farmers. Those three
concerts raised more than $10 million for farmers. But no such
concert will be held in 1988, and Nelson said it is unlikely there
will ever be another Farm Aid show.
   ``I never say `never,' but right now it's time for the
politicians to do their share,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CLAYTON, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Frances ``Tut'' Woodruff, known for a court
battle for her share of the Coca-Cola fortune and her passion for
hang gliding, has started an ambulance service.
   The 64-year-old heiress was attending a Rabun County Commission
meeting when a woman complained the publicly subsidized ambulance
service wouldn't take her husband from a Clayton hospital to one
outside the county.
   Commissioners said the service had a policy against leaving the
county.
   ``I was very hurt that this lady couldn't get help from the
county,'' Miss Woodruff said.
   That prompted the birth of the Blue Ridge Emergency Service this
month. Miss Woodruff quickly hired all the emergency medical
technicians away from the public service, and that service has been
discontinued.
   ``We're glad she took it,'' said Claude Kelly, chairman of the
Rabun County Hospital Authority. ``She stole a headache from us.
It'll save the taxpayers $70,000 a year.''
   Kelly said he has no resentment toward Miss Woodruff, but added
that ``when she gets tired of playing with it and losing two or
three hundred thousand dollars a year and is ready to get rid of
it, then we'll start ours back again.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``In life there are some people you meet whom
you'd just like to pal around with. They're fun, they put you in a
good frame of mind, and they make you feel terrific,'' Lee Iacocca
writes in his new book ``Talking Straight.''
   ``Well, that's Ronald Reagan. He's not Dr. Strangelove _ He's
Dr. Feelgood. I want him to be my pal. But not my president.''
   The book, due out in June, is excerpted in the May 30 issue of
People magazine. The Chrysler Corp. chairman's previous book,
``Iacocca,'' sold 2.6 million copies.
   The new book covers more recent events in his life and politics.
Iacocca talks about the 1983 death of his wife of 27 years, his
short-lived second marriage, his struggles with Don Regan while
Regan was treasury secretary and his predictions for the 1988
presidential race.
   Iacocca says he thought of running for the country's top spot
himself, but decided against it.
   So who does Iacocca expect to occupy the White House?
   ``The odds are overpowering that we're going to have a very
activist Democratic president. I don't think the Republicans can
make it.''
</TEXT>
