<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Afghanistan     05-22 0392</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Afghanistan,0404</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Final Soviet Troops Leave Jalalabad</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: One name cq for Najib</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The last Soviet troops on Sunday pulled out of
Jalalabad and arrived in the capital, Kabul, the Tass news agency
reported.
   The withdrawal paved the way for a rebel attack on Jalalabad, a
strategic northeastern city. Anti-communist forces have said they
would invade Jalalabad once the Soviet troops were gone.
   Tass said withdrawal of the convoy left no Soviet troops in the
province of Nangarhar, in northeast Afghanistan near the border
with Pakistan.
   The brief dispatch did not say how many troops were in the
convoy, the latest in a series to make the 88-mile trip to Kabul
from Jalalabad.
   The convoy will rest in the capital before traveling an
additional 200 miles to the Soviet city of Termez.
   The first convoy headed out from Jalalabad on May 15 and was
greeted in Kabul with marching bands and speeches by Afghan
officials, including President Najib.
   On Saturday, Tass said, a second military unit from Afghanistan
arrived in Termez and was welcomed by relatives and friends, city
officials and youth delegations from several Soviet republics.
   Under an agreement signed in Geneva on April 14, an estimated
115,000 Soviet soldiers who have been helping the Afghan government
in its war with anti-Marxist guerrillas are to be out within nine
months.
   The Communist Party daily Pravda on Sunday repeated what has
become daily Soviet media criticism of the United States and
Pakistan for continuing to supply weapons to the guerrillas who
have been fighting the Kabul government since a 1978 communist coup.
   ``The heart of the Geneva agreements, on which stand the
signatures of representatives of the U.S.A. and Pakistan, is simple
and understandable: the fate of Afghanistan should be decided by
the Afghan people themselves, and only themselves,'' Pravda said.
   The newspaper cited Western reports that the Afghan rebels are
feverishly shipping military equipment from bases in Pakistan to
facilities in Afghanistan.
   It said ``several hotheads'' in Washington are discussing how
the rebels will take control of Afghan cities and form a
provisional government. But the rebels are not as strong as some
people in the West think, Pravda said, and the predictions of
victory are overly optimistic.
   Soviet soldiers entered Afghanistan in December 1979, replaced
one pro-Kremlin government with another and remained to fight the
insurgency.
</TEXT>
