<DOCNO> AP880522-0034 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-22-88 1454EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Shultz-Summit     05-22 0735</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shultz-Summit,710</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shultz Urges Senate To Approve Arms Pact Before Summit</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Gorbachev Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State George Shultz, saying it's
``time to decide,'' urged the Senate on Sunday to approve the
U.S.-Soviet treaty banning medium-range nuclear missiles in time
for the summit between Mikhail Gorbachev and President Reagan.
   The secretary of state also echoed the positive remarks
Gorbachev made in an interview with U.S. reporters, in which the
Soviet leader said he hoped he could sign an agreement slashing in
half the superpower arsenals of strategic nuclear weapons before
Reagan leaves office.
   ``It's certainly possible,'' Shultz said of prospects for such a
treaty. Speaking on ABC-TV's ``This Week With David Brinkley,'' the
secretary added: ``And I feel certain that at the Moscow summit we
will both want to agree to keep working on it hard. But whether it
will actually happen or not, I don't know. The issues are tough.''
   The president leaves Wednesday, stopping first in Helsinki,
Finland, before traveling on to Moscow for the May 29-June 2 summit.
   Queried about talks on the disputed Strategic Defense
Initiative, which has hampered agreement on a strategic missile
pact, Shultz said Reagan has staunchly opposed any impediment to
the development of a defense against ballistic missiles.
   ``That still leaves room for a lot of things,'' the secretary
said, pointing to a ``period of non-withdrawal'' from the
Anti-Ballistic Missile treaty, which the Soviets contend bars
certain elements of the president's space-based missile defense
program, also known as Star Wars.
   On Saturday, Reagan used his radio address to appeal for
ratification of the medium-range missile treaty, formally known as
the pact on Intermediate Range Nuclear Forces.
   It was signed by the two leaders at their December summit in
Washington and administration officials are eager to display the
ratified treaty as a boost for the president in his negotiations
with Gorbachev.
   While the Senate has turned aside a wave of amendments designed
by its conservative opponents to kill the treaty, debate is
expected to continue through much of the week. Approval of the pact
requires 67 votes, if all 100 senators are present.
   Shultz, who is to carry his campaign for the pact to Capitol
Hill on Monday, pointed out that more than a dozen years have
passed since the United States has ratified a treaty with the
Soviet Union, and that it would help the president in his efforts
at the summit if the treaty were approved.
   ``It helps certainly to have completed something and to register
that fact. ... It's good to register the fact that we can do it,''
Shultz said.
   The secretary, avoiding any criticism of the president's
conservative allies who oppose the treaty, lauded the Senate for
its thorough consideration of the pact.
   ``I think the process has gone well. I have only compliments for
the Senate and the way in which they've handled this,'' he said,
adding, ``I think there's been a time for hearings, a time for
questions, a time for critiques and a time for debate. There also
has to come a time to decide and I think we're about there.''
   Appearing on the same program, Sen. Sam Nunn, D-Ga., chairman of
the Armed Services Committee, said he believed the treaty will be
ready in time for the two leaders to sign.
   ``We will finish the INF treaty, prior not to the president
departing, but prior to the actual meetings,'' he said, adding,
``That's a guess and I give it 60-40 odds.''
   Senate Whip Alan Cranston, D-Calif., said he's counted some 78
``very firm'' votes for the treaty. ``I don't think the president
should go empty-handed,'' said Cranston, appearing on NBC-TV's
``Meet The Press.''
   On the same show, treaty opponent Sen. Gordon Humphrey, R-N.H.,
called the pact ``very one-sided and very, very dangerous,'' and
one that would allow the Soviets an unfair advantage.
   The spokesman for the Soviet Foreign Ministry, Gennady
Gerasimov, said on the same show that U.S. officials had predicted
at the December summit that the treaty would be ratified by April.
   ``And now it is May. We simply expect, that if you promise then
you must deliver. But we also understand your political system,''
Gerasimov said.
   He said it would be considered ``a good sign of your willingness
to improve relations between our countries if you ratify the treaty
by the time of the Moscow summit.''
</TEXT>
