<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Pakistan-Fighting     05-22 0343</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pakistan-Fighting,0353</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Officials Say Five Dead In Clashes Between Rival Moslem Groups</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At least five people died in
gunfights between Shiite and Sunni Moslems in a resort town in
mountainous northern Pakistan, the government said Sunday.
   ``There is still a lot of tension which we have to watch out
for,'' said a high-ranking Pakistani official, speaking on
condition of anonymity.
   The official said at least five people had died in fighting in
the town of Gilgit since Tuesday. U.S. officials in Islamabad said
Saturday that up to 14 people may have died.
   Army troops were flown Sunday into Gilgit, 155 miles north of
the Pakistani capital of Islamabad, to enforce a 24-hour curfew,
said Western tourists arriving from the area.
   Britt Wilder, a Danish woman who was one of six tourists who
flew from Gilgit to Islamabad on Sunday, said 88 others were
awaiting flights out of the area.
   She said the town appeared quiet Sunday and that tourists were
not threatened in the fighting, which was centered in the town's
bazaar.
   Pakistan International Airlines spokemen said they were
scheduling as many flights as weather permitted. The commercial
carrier flies in and out of the rugged area only in clear weather
because of steep mountain peaks that surround the town.
   A U.S. official on Saturday said the Pakistan military had
offered to evacuate foreigners on C-130 transport planes if the
commercial airline was unable to fly.
   Returning tourists, mainly foreign diplomats and their
dependents based in Islamabad, said the trouble started Tuesday and
continued throughout the week in an apparent dispute over the end
of the Moslem holy month of Ramadan.
   The breaking of the monthlong dawn-to-dusk fasting is determined
by the sighting of the new moon. The Moslem clergymen who are
appointed the task of ending Ramadan often disagree on the day.
   However, officials said it was the first time in recent memory
that it has sparked violence.
   Most of the country's 96 million people are Sunni Moslems.
Shiites comprise an estimated 15 percent of the population.
</TEXT>
