<HEAD>Government Orders ICRC To Free Stored Relief Food</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ADDIS ABABA, Ethiopia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government has given the
International Committee of the Red Cross 15 days to free tons of
relief food and other items locked in its stores in the war-torn
northern provinces of Tigre and Eritrea.
   The Ministry of Foreign Affairs said in letter to Jean-Jacque
Fresard, Red Cross representative in Ethiopia, that the stored food
is ``unjustifiably sustaining damage as a result of the
indifference, deliberately and consciously, pursued by ICRC.''
   The letter told the Red Cross that the government will take any
measure it considers appropriate if the food is not handed over to
Ethiopian authorities within 15 days.
   Ethiopia in early April ordered all foreign relief workers out
of Eritrea and Tigre for security reasons. Four U.N. Workers were
allowed to continue relief operations after a senior U.N. official
met with President Mengistu Haile Mariam.
   Rebels have been fighting for 27 years in Eritrea and for 14
years in Tigre.
   The order for relief workers to leave was issued as the
government prepared for a counteroffensive following a series of
victories by the rebels.
   International Red Cross first said it was defying the order to
recall its 25 or so workers, citing a ``humanitarian responsibility
for the fate of some 5 million people'' in the two drought-stricken
provinces.
   When the government insisted that the Red Cross workers leave
the areas, the agency locked up its supplies and trucks and left.
   Red Cross officials have denied earlier requests to hand over
the food because they said they must be present to supervise the
food's distribution. In the past, there have been allegations that
food destined for starving farmers has gone to feed Ethiopian
soldiers.
</TEXT>
