<HEAD>Vietnam Marks Party Founder's Birthday By Urging Reform</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vietnam's Communist Party marked the
98th birthday of the late Ho Chi Minh by declaring a commitment to
reforming the party that he founded, Vietnamese radio reported
Sunday.
   The main aim of reform is to improve leadership and management
of the faltering economy, the official party newspaper Nhan Dan
said in an editorial to mark Ho's birthday Thursday.
   A text of a Radio Hanoi broadcast quoting the editorial was seen
in Bangkok on Sunday.
   The editorial said the party must not only ``renovate'' its
thinking, but find cadres qualified to forge ahead with pragmatic
economic reforms endorsed at the December 1986 sixth national party
congress.
   It urged a struggle against ``the two major dangers of the
ruling party _ the evil of bureaucratism, despotism and oppression
of the people, and the evil of embezzling the property of the
state, collectives and the people.''
   Ho founded the party in 1930 and led it to victories against the
French and the Japanese. He died in 1969, six years before the
communists won the war against U.S.-backed South Vietnam and
reunified the country.
   In the newly self-critical atmosphere under pragmatic party
chief Nguyen Van Linh, the party has made unprecedented admissions
of malaise, corruption, and ineptitude among its ranks. Vietnamese
officials say thousands have been purged from the
1.8-million-member party in the past year.
