<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Obit-Patzelt     05-22 0231</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Patzelt,0237</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Priest Who Performed Exorcism Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS GATOS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Rev. Karl Patzelt, a Catholic
priest who performed an exorcism for a Daly City family in 1973,
has died at 71.
   Patzelt died Thursday at the Sacred Heart Jesuit Center, where
he lived two years after Alzheimer's disease forced him to give up
his parish.
   The Austrian-born former pastor of Our Lady of Fatima Byzantine
Catholic Church in San Francisco, drew widespread publicity when it
was reported that he performed exorcism rites 14 times ``before a
great wave of heat hit the room and the household returned to
normal.''
   He said he visited the Daly City family's home and found
exterior signs of the devil, such as broken windows, marks and
dents on the walls caused by flying boots, knives and ``any other
object the devil could grab.''
   During the first seven exorcisms, the devil ``revealed
himself,'' he said. The couple were revived from unconsciousness
only by the touch of a relic of the Holy Cross, he said.
   Patzelt was drafted into the German army during World War II and
spent five years in a prisoner-of-war camp in the Soviet Union. He
came to the United States in 1957 to finish his religious training.
   He is survived by three brothers, Rudolf, Fritz and George
Patzelt; a niece, Monika Lovgren; and a nephew, Leo Patzelt, all of
Sweden.
</TEXT>
