<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Poland-Marshall     05-22 0284</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poland-Marshall,0291</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Polish Party Newspaper Rejects New Marshall Plan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Communist Party newspaper has rejected
a new proposed Marshall plan for Poland in exchange for
Western-inspired democratic reform, calling the idea ``alms that
would in addition subjugate Poland politically.''
   ``Are we today going to experience new dependence (on the West)
served in the wrapping of a new Marshall Plan?'' Trybuna Ludu said
in a commentary in its weekend edition. ``This would be stupidity
bordering on madness.''
   Several Western political commentators and leaders, including
former French President Valery Giscard d'Estaing, suggested the
idea of a Western bailout during Polish labor unrest from April 25
to May 10. Such a plan would help Poland with its huge foreign debt
in exchange for democratization and other political reforms.
   The 1948-51 Marshall Plan, named after U.S. Secretary of State
George Marshall, distributed $12 billion in foreign aid from the
United States to rebuild Western Europe after World War II. The
plan offered help to Poland and other Eastern European countries,
but it was rejected under pressure from the Soviet Union, which saw
it as a bid to bring those nations under American influence.
   Poland struggles with a foreign debt of $39 billion, an aging
industrial base, 45 percent inflation, and average incomes of about
$100 a month. Its leaders have long been critical of Western
countries, saying they should do more to help.
   But Trybuna Ludu, the chief paper of the governing Polish United
Workers Party, said the government would not sacrifice political
beliefs for Western aid.
   Such a plan is intended to ``change the power alignment in
Europe'' and represents ``an attempt to make a vassal out of
Poland,'' the newspaper said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
