<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Spain-Protest     05-22 0204</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Spain-Protest,0212</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thousands Protest Spanish Entry into Western Alliance</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands marched through the capital
Sunday to protest the nation's planned entry into a Western
European military alliance.
   The organization, known as the Western European Union, is
designed to increase cooperation among European members of NATO and
promote discussion of defense issues facing Western Europe.
   Leftist political parties, labor unions, pacifists and anti-NATO
groups called the march to pressure the government of Socialist
Prime Minister Felipe Gonzalez to stay out of the seven-nation
alliance.
   The government has scheduled participation to begin within a
year, with negotiations under way by autumn.
   Protesters marched Sunday behind large banners bearing the
slogans ``No to entry in the WEU,'' ``For total denuclearization''
and ``The (NATO) referendum has not been complied with.''
   In recent weeks, leftist and centrist political parties and
other groups have said the government's acceptance of port visits
by U.S. Navy ships violates the conditions of Spain's membership in
NATO. Spain bans storage or transport of nuclear weapons on its
territory.
   Organizers estimated Sunday's crowd at 5,000, but municipal
police put the number at 2,000. Police reported no violence.
   The alliance includes Britain, the Netherlands, Luxembourg,
France, Belgium, West Germany and Italy.
</TEXT>
