<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     05-22 0427</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0439</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thunderstorms Lash Gulf Coast; Rain Scattered Through Central,
Eastern U.S.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Severe thunderstorms lashed the central Gulf Coast again Sunday
while showers and thunderstorms also were scattered over the
central Plains and the mid-Atlantic states.
   While cloudy skies prevailed across the eastern two thirds of
the country, it was sunny over much of the West.
   Thunderstorms moved out of Texas across Louisiana and into
Mississippi during the morning, producing hail and strong winds.
The storms were expected to continue into Sunday night.
   Showers and scattered thunderstorms also hit much of Arkansas
and Missouri, and showers were prevalent across the central Plains.
   Memphis, Tenn., received 0.80 inch of rain in the six hours
ended 2 p.m. EDT and Lincoln, Neb., got a half inch in the same
period.
   In the Northeast, there were scattered showers and thunderstorms
in New York State, eastern Pennsylvania, northern New Jersey and
western New England in the early afternoon. Altoona, Pa., recorded
just over half an inch of rain in the six hours ending at 2 p.m.
EDT.
   A few showers and thunderstorms lingered along the southern
Atlantic Coast, and a few showers also were developing ahead of a
cold front entering the northern Pacific Coast.
   Temperatures were in the 80s in the thunderstorm areas of the
central Gulf Coast and the southern Atlantic Coast, as well as in
southern Texas and the Ohio Valley. Readings climbed into the 90s
and over 100 degrees in the Southwest deserts.
   Early afternoon temperatures were only in the upper 40s and 50s
in parts of the central Plains and Colorado and Wyoming.
   At 3 p.m. EDT, temperatures ranged from 48 degrees at Goodland,
Kan., to 105 degrees at Palm Springs, Calif.
   Monday's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms to extend
from northern Florida and the central Gulf Coast to the
mid-Atlantic Coast and southern sections of the Great Lakes, with
the heaviest concentration in the Ohio Valley. Scattered showers
and thunderstorms also were forecast for the middle Mississippi
Valley to Oklahoma, Kansas and Nebraska. Fair to partly sunny skies
were predicted for the rest of the nation.
   Highs were forecast to be in the 60s in the central Plains and
lower Missouri Valley, and in the Pacific Northwest; and in the 80s
from the central Gulf Coast to the mid-Atlantic Coast, in North
Dakota and much of Montana, and from interior California to
southern and central Texas, with highs climbing into the 90s or
above 100 in the Southwest deserts.
   Elsewhere, highs were predicted to be in the 70s.
</TEXT>
