<1ST_LINE>r a AM-GunBill     05-22 0432</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gun Bill,0443</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ceremony Planned for Signing of Gun Control Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM STUCKEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANNAPOLIS, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Uniformed police officers will form a
backdrop and presidential press secretary James Brady will look on
in an elaborate ceremony planned for signing of a bill banning the
sale of cheap handguns in Maryland.
   Gov. William Donald Schaefer plans to sign the bill Monday at
the Maryland State House, where more than 200 police officers are
expected to take part, said Luther Starnes, Schaefer's assistant
press secretary.
   The main speaker will be Sarah Brady, who became active in
gun-control efforts nationally after her husband was seriously
wounded in the assassination attempt on President Reagan by John
Hinckley Jr.
   Legislative leaders and other officials who helped push the bill
through the General Assembly last month also have been invited.
   Schaefer aides say the ceremony is not intended to send a
message to pro-gun groups that are collecting signatures on
petitions to place the bill on the ballot for a public vote in
November.
   State officials characterize the bill as unique in that it sets
up a board to determine what handguns can be sold in Maryland
beginning in 1990. It will be legal to possess guns approved by the
review board, but it will be against the law for anyone, including
private owners, to sell weapons not on the approved list.
   The law is primarily aimed at the cheap handguns, known as
Saturday night specials, that are often used in street crimes.
   The review board also is directed to omit from the list of
approved guns any weapons that have the serial number removed or
altered and guns made primarily of plastic that aren't easily
detected by metal detectors.
   Weldon Clark, founder of a group called Stop Gun Prohibition,
said his group is convinced it can easily collect the 33,044
signatures needed to force a referendum on the bill in November.
   Ted Lattanzio, the NRA's director of state and local affairs,
said the bill was steamrolled through the Legislature in an
atmosphere of emotional hysteria.
   He said the public was deluded ``into thinking it (the bill)
will have an impact on crime, which it won't.''
   Vincent Demarco, who resigned as an assistant state attorney
general to head Marylanders Against Handgun Abuse, said his group
is concerned about a referendum even though public opinion polls
show overwhelming support for a ban on the sale of Saturday night
specials.
   ``The NRA has won referendums in other states by spending a lot
of money and misrepresenting the situation and telling people
falsehoods,'' he said.
</TEXT>
