<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Netherlands-Chess     05-22 0428</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Netherlands-Chess,0444</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kasparov Leads Karpov in Dutch Chess Tournament</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AMSTERDAM, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   World chess champion Gary Kasparov
defeated a dogged Dutch opponent Sunday to stake out a one-point
lead against archrival Anatoly Karpov in a four-player contest.
   Kasparov's seventh-round victory came against John van der Wiel
and gave him the tournament lead over Anatoly Karpov, a fellow
Soviet who is ranked second in the world. Karpov was held to a draw
Sunday by Dutch champion Jan Timman, ranked third in the world.
   The four-way contest pits the world's two leading players for
the first time since Kasparov retained his title last year in
Seville, Spain. He beat Karpov in 1985 to become world champion.
   The tournament also marks Kasparov's return to the international
tournament arena after a nearly yearlong absence.
   Playing white against Van der Wiel's Queen's Indian defense,
Kasparov soon got the upper hand Sunday. He forced his opponent
into a cramped position and devastated his Queen's side pawn
structure, while gradually improving his own array.
   Halfway through the game, Van der Wiel compounded his own
problems by running into time trouble, and Kasparov seemed ready to
deliver the coup de grace. He grabbed control of the center and
sacrificed an exchange to storm black's King's side.
   But with under 10 minutes on the clock for 20 moves separating
him from time control, Van der Wiel dug in his heels. A desperate
counter-offensive almost forced Kasparov to return all his spoils.
   But when the Dutchman made it to the time check, it turned out
that the world champion had nicely calculated his chances. With
four pawns against his opponent's three, he was in winning position.
   Van der Wiel resigned on his 45th, when he stood to lose another
pawn or go mate.
   Karpov's encounter with Timman was more routine. Sometimes
called ``vice-world champion,'' Karpov played black with his pet
Caro-Kann defense and easily held the balance throughout the
opening.
   Exasperated by Karpov's conservative defensive play, Timman
initiated a risky variation but got nowhere.
   The two players continued until the 43rd, exchanging pieces
without really changing anything and then agreed to the draw.
   Kasparov was left in first place with five points and a record
of three wins and four draws, while Karpov tallied four with two
wins, four draws and a loss.
   Timman was third with 3{ points and Van der Wiel last with 1{.
   The tournament, organized by the Amsterdam European Options
Exchange for its 10th anniversary, was to continue Monday. Kasparov
plays Timman with white, and Karpov faces Van der Wiel with black.
</TEXT>
