<1ST_LINE>r a AM-US-RussianPaintings     05-22 0281</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Russian Paintings,0287</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>American, Soviet Publishers Announce Avant-Guard Exhibit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of Russian avant-guard paintings banned
from public view since 1932 will be displayed in Leningrad and
published under a joint American-Soviet project this fall,
publishers said.
   The collection of Russian avant-guard art, including previously
unexhibited works by Kandinsky and Malevich, is believed to be the
largest ever to be displayed in that country or published in the
West, Paul Gottleib, publisher at Harry N. Abrams Inc., said at a
news conference here Friday.
   The company is producing the art book in conjunction with
Sovietsky Khudozhnik, the Soviet art publishing house.
   Nearly all the artworks were produced legally before 1932, when
the All-Union Congress of Artists succumbed to a cultural chill
under Stalin and decreed that only ``Socialist Realism'' would be
appropriate in the young communist country.
   ``We professionals knew about this art even in the worst times.
But now, (under glasnost, the new policy of openness) the general
audience is interested in anything ... particularly of the period''
before Stalin, said Mikhail Anikst, creative director of the book
project.
   Gottleib, Anikst and Vladimir Viktorovich Gorianov, a Soviet
publisher, showed photographs of the works at the news conference.
   The works of more than 170 artists, most of whom are dead, will
be displayed for at least three months in Leningrad but will not
travel to other Soviet museums. No plans have been set for taking
the exhibit outside the country, Gorianov said.
   Many Russian avant-guard artists, who were among the leaders
worldwide at the time, continued to work illegally after 1932 and
marked the birth of Russian underground art, said Phyllis Freemam,
an editor of the book.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
