<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BRF--RareTurtle     05-22 0157</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Rare Turtle,0160</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>One of Rarely Seen Leatherbacks, 700 Pounds and Six Feet Long,
Found Dead</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHANNEL ISLANDS NATIONAL PARK, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A rare leatherback
sea turtle, which weighed 700 pounds and was six feet long, has
been found dead on a beach at Santa Rosa Island off the California
coast.
   The turtle, which spends much of its life hundreds of miles
offshore, was only the third leatherback found on Southern
California beaches in the last 15 years. All were dead.
   The discovery was made last week by Bill Ehorn, superintendent
of Channel Islands National Park.
   Leatherbacks, which weigh up to 2,000 pounds, are believed to
live as long as 100 years.
   Gary Davis, 43, marine biologist for the park, removed the skull
and bones Thursday and sent them to the Santa Barbara Museum of
Natural History, where they will be held for scientists to study.
His autopsy did not determine the cause of death.
</TEXT>
