<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SAfrica-Minerals     05-22 0280</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-SAfrica-Minerals ,0289</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Opposition Politician Seeks Halt in Mineral Sales to United States</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A right-wing government
opponent on Sunday called for suspending strategic mineral sales to
the United States in response to threats of heavier U.S. economic
sanctions.
   Clive Derby-Lewis of the Conservative Party urged a ban on sales
of platinum and other key minerals that the United States obtains
primarily from South Africa.
   ``Why should South Africa kowtow to the U.S.?'' he said in a
statement. The United States ``is deliberately undermining the
economy of South Africa at great cost to all of its inhabitants.''
   ``The United States is cynically oblivious to the double
standards inherent in their policy of normal trade with the
Communist Bloc countries, who have no record whatsoever of human
rights beliefs,'' Derby-Lewis said.
   The U.S. Congress is weighing a sanctions package that would cut
most bilateral economic ties in a bid to pressure South Africa into
speeding up race reform. In 1986, Congress placed limited sanctions
on South Africa.
   South Africa supplies about 80 percent of the platinum sold to
the non-communist world. It has the world's largest known reserves
of strategic minerals such as manganese, chromium, vanadium and
titanium.
   The world's other main supplier of strategic minerals is the
Soviet Union.
   Foreign Minister Rolef ``Pik'' Botha reiterated last week the
government has no intention of withholding strategic minerals to
Western nations, even if they impose sanctions.
   By law and custom, South Africa's apartheid policies have
established a racially segregated society in which the 26 million
blacks have no vote in national affairs. The 5 million whites
control the economy and maintain separate districts, schools and
health services.
</TEXT>
