<1ST_LINE>u a AM-SchoolShootings 2ndLd-Writethru a0838 05-22 0843</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-School Shootings, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0838,0865</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Laurie Dann Sought Revenge, Experts Say</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 4 grafs for 6th graf pvs ``She probably'' to UPDATE with
teacher's comments on saving children; picks up 7th graf pvs,
``Visotsky said ...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ELIZABETH SHOGREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WINNETKA, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Laurie Dann's last day of life had a
fearful toll: one child dead and six people wounded, a house fire
and deliveries of poisoned food. Now authorities are struggling to
understand her state of mind.
   ``This is a seriously destroyed individual who lost control and
acted out all of her delusions,'' said Harold Visotsky, professor
and chairman of the department of psychiatry at Northwestern
University Medical School.
   Ms. Dann shot herself to death Friday after killing an
8-year-old boy and wounding five other children in a rampage at
Hubbard Woods Elementary School north of Chicago.
   She also shot a 20-year-old man who tried to wrest a gun from
her at a home nearby.
   Shortly before the shootings, she delivered arsenic-laced snacks
and juice to two Northwestern University fraternities and several
homes where she had worked as a babysitter. There were no serious
injuries.
   Police said the death toll might have been higher had it not
been for the actions of a substitute teacher at the elementary
school who refused Dann's order to herd together the 24 children in
her room. Instead, the teacher grabbed the assailant's gun hand,
but Ms. Dann pulled out a second pistol and opened fire.
   ``I just acted instinctually. I just wanted to protect the
children,'' said the 29-year-old teacher, Amy Moses.
   At a news conference Sunday, Ms. Moses said: ``I really just
went on automatic pilot. ... I can't explain how unreal the whole
situation was.''
   In an interview Sunday, Visotsky said Ms. Dann ``probably had a
symbolic reason for every one of (the acts of violence).''
   Visotsky said that Ms. Dann probably saw herself as a victim and
sought revenge against those who had ``diminished her sense of
self-worth.''
   Police Chief Herbert Timm said: ``There obviously is a
connection with children here. We don't know what.''
   Elizabeth Kaufman, an acquaintance, said Sunday, ``I know that
she felt that she had no one to talk to.
   ``I always thought she was a little bit odd, but I always
thought she was harmless. She was a nice person,'' Ms. Kaufman said
in a telephone interview from Lubbock, Texas, where she recently
moved.
   ``She was always trying to help people to be happy, which is
what's so strange about this.''
   Meanwhile, members of the clergy used Sunday services to pray
for the victims and Ms. Dann. Six victims remained hospitalized,
four in serious condition and one in critical condition, officials
said.
   ``Today we will pray for Laurie Dann because, for what she did,
she could not have been in her right mind,'' the Rev. Mike Weston
of Sacred Heart Catholic Church said. ``And because she was once a
child and a Christian and ... because Jesus prayed for his
enemies.''
   Visotsky agreed with police who believe the chain of violence
probably was triggered when Ms. Dann learned a family for whom she
babysat planned to leave Illinois.
   Police said that on the morning of the shootings, Ms. Dann set a
small fire in the family's house and gave tainted milk to two of
the family's children.
   But her troubles had begun sooner.
   Authorities in Arizona were ready to indict Ms. Dann on charges
of making threatening phone calls to a former boyfriend, and Lake
County, Ill., prosecutors planned similar charges in another case.
   In Madison, Wis., where Ms. Dann often lived, police said they
interviewed her five days before she died after they received
reports she was acting erratically.
   Capt. Jeffrey Frye said three Madison officers and a resident
manager at The Towers, a private dormitory complex near the
University of Wisconsin-Madison campus, entered Ms. Dann's room May
15 with a master key and talked with her.
   Someone earlier had found her ``in a storage room in The Towers
covered with a plastic bag and sweating profusely,'' Frye said.
   ``They determined there wasn't a whole lot they could do with
her,'' he said.
   ``We had gotten some information ... that she may have a weapon
or may have access to a .357-Magnum,'' Frye said. No gun was found,
he said.
   Ms. Dann was due to stand trial in Madison on charges of
shoplifting several women's wigs March 14.
   Greg Rogers, owner of a card shop in Madison, said Saturday that
official-looking letters addressed to Ms. Dann at his store have
been arriving for about 10 weeks. But he said he did not know her
or why mail for her would be coming to his address.
   Dr. Joseph Flaherty, professor of psychiatry and preventive
medicine at the University of Illinois-Chicago, said Ms. Dann may
have suffered from a borderline personality disorder or paranoid
psychosis.
   People who suffer from these disorders ``develop a strong
feeling that they have been wronged, that people are against them
and they should retaliate,'' he said.
</TEXT>
