<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WomanElectrocuted     05-22 0245</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Woman Electrocuted,0251</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Woman Electrocuted During Phone Conversation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MONTEZUMA, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 22-year-old pregnant woman was killed
while talking on the telephone when a bolt of lightning struck the
phone lines outside her house, authorities said.
   Laura McDowell, who was eight months pregnant, and the fetus
died from lightning that struck about 5 p.m. Saturday as a heavy
band of thunderstorms moved through the central New York region,
Cayuga County sheriff's deputies said. Emergency room doctors were
unable to resuscitate Ms. McDowell, Auburn Memorial Hospital
nursing supervisor Nancy Purdy said.
   Ms. McDowell's 3-year-old daughter witnessed her mother's death
and several of the victim's relatives were sitting in the living
room when the accident occurred.
   Ms. McDowell's stepbrother, Allen Harmon, 17, told authorities
the bolt knocked things off the wall and threw Ms. McDowell from
the chair in which she was sitting.
   The phone was blackened by the electrical charge, which
authorities estimated was between 10,000 and 50,000 volts. About 50
volts can jog the human heart.
   Howard G. Williams, a spokesman for New York Telephone Co., said
such a fatality was rare because although telephone lines carry low
voltages, they are grounded and insulated against transporting
strong electrical charges.
   However, Williams cautioned that it is still unwise to talk on
the telephone during a thunderstorm because electricity can be
drawn into the home on its way to the ground.
   Authorities said the exact cause of McDowell's death would be
determined with an autopsy.
</TEXT>
