<FILEID>AP-NR-05-22-88 2053EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Ireland-Britain     05-22 0399</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ireland-Britain,0413</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fugitive Condemns Extradition Policy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DUBLIN, Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fugitive Irish nationalist wanted on a
murder charge held a clandestine news conference Sunday near the
Northern Ireland border to condemn the British-Irish extradition
treaty, an Irish news agency reported.
   Security officials, hearing of the meeting, ordered an immediate
intensification of the hunt for Patrick McIntyre, a member of the
outlawed Irish Republican Army.
   The 30-year-old fugitive met with journalists at a whitewashed
farmhouse in remote mountain country about 20 miles from the border
in County Donegal, the news agency Ireland International said.
   The handful of reporters were instructed by an anonymous tipoff
to drive to a road near McIntyre's hometown, Letterkenny, then were
driven in a blacked-out van for a half-hour to the secret farmhouse
meeting, the agency said.
   ``Irish citizens can be arrested on the word of the British
government and extradited. There are no safety measures. Any Irish
citizen can be arrested solely on an extradition warrant,'' the
agency quoted McIntyre as saying.
   Britain announced May 13 that Ireland had agreed to resume
extradition of terrorist suspects, following a five-month wrangle
over legal procedures.
   The two governments have long been at odds over the Irish
Republic's reluctance to extradite suspects sought for trial in
connection with the IRA's bloody battle to end British rule of
Protestant-dominated Northern Ireland.
   The mainly Roman Catholic guerrilla group wants to unite the
province with the Irish Republic, which is predominantly Catholic.
   McIntyre, unshaven and clad in jeans and a T-shirt, added that
although on the run he had no intention of leaving Ireland. ``I
don't believe the British government should force an Irish citizen
out of his country,'' the agency quoted him as saying.
   He is wanted on 21 charges, including murder, in connection with
the 1983 mass escape from Maze Prison in Northern Ireland, where he
had been serving a 15-year sentence for the attempted murder of a
part-time soldier.
   McIntyre had been recaptured 24 hours after the breakout in
which a guard was killed, but fled custody while on Christmas
parole in 1986.
   He was re-arrested by Irish police, but walked free from the
High Court in Dublin in May 1987 after a judge ruled he had been
unlawfully arrested. He was driven off at high speed on a
motorcycle and has not been seen since, although he is still being
sought on extradition warrants.
</TEXT>
