<HEAD>Flight Aborted After Light Indicated Problem with Wing Slats</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GRAPEVINE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The pilot of an American Airlines DC-10
carrying 254 people aborted his takeoff because a warning light
indicated a problem with the jumbo jet's wing slats, an airline
spokesman said Sunday.
   ``I understand that the warning light had to do with ... the
leading edge slats'' over the front of the wing, American spokesman
John Hotard said.
   Hotard said the airline would investigate whether there was a
problem with the slats or if the warning light itself malfunctioned.
   Officials from the National Transportation Safety Board took the
cockpit recorders from the plane Sunday night and turned the
aircraft over to the airline, which faces the difficult task of
removing it from the field beyond the runway.
   Flight 70, bound for Frankfurt, West Germany, ran off the
runway, its front landing gear collapsed in the rain-softened grass
and the aircraft skidded 1,000 feet on its nose to a stop.
   The airline planned to remove the plane later Sunday or Monday,
a ``very laborious project'' that will require support for the
front of the plane, Hotard said.
   The plane was not preventing other traffic from using the
runway, officials said.
   Capt. Bob Cornelison was held for observation overnight at
Baylor Medical Center and was released Sunday, a Baylor spokesman
said. Two other members of the flight crew and three passengers
were treated for minor injuries and released from local hospitals
Saturday.
</TEXT>
