<HEAD>Member of Parliament Shot Dead</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A member of the mixed-race
chamber of Parliament was fatally shot in his car Sunday night by
an unknown assailant, police said.
   Police said Peter Sam Jacobs, a member of the majority Labor
Party in the House of Representatives, was shot while returning
from a meeting at a church to his home near Alberton, southeast of
Johannesburg.
   Police said the window of Jacobs' car had been smashed by the
attacker, but gave no indication who the killer was and what the
motive might have been.
   Jacobs, whose age was not immediately available, was elected to
Parliament in 1984 after a new constitution was adopted creating
chambers for Asians and mixed-race people along with the existing
chamber for whites.
   The new constitution continued to exclude the black majority
from national politics. Anti-apartheid activists of all races
organized a boycott of the Asian and mixed-race elections which
helped keep the turnout below 20 percent.
   The Labor Party has remained estranged from the mainstream of
the anti-apartheid movement, although its leader, the Rev. Allan
Hendrickse, has taken an increasingly confrontational stance toward
President P.W. Botha in the past year while demanding abolition of
apartheid legislation.
   Under apartheid law and custom, South Africa's 26 million blacks
have no vote in national affairs while the country's 5 million
whites control the economy and maintain separate districts, schools
and health services.
</TEXT>
