<2ND_LINE>AM-Georgia GOP, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0861,360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dispute Could Leave State Party With Two Delegations To Convention</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2 grafs for last graf pvs to UPDATE with comment from
GOP counsel.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ELLIOTT MINOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Georgia's Republican Party could be left with
two competing delegations to the party's national convention in New
Orleans this summer, in the wake of a weekend dispute at the state
GOP convention.
   Atlanta lawyer Matt Patton took the podium at Saturday's party
convention after an angry walkout by GOP Chairman John Stuckey, who
adjourned the meeting and left along with several hundred party
regulars.
   The more than 900 Republicans who remained elected Patton to
preside and continued the convention on their own, adopting a party
platform and electing 18 at-large delegates to the National
Republican Convention in New Orleans.
   Stuckey said he would convene a meeting of the party's state
executive committee to select the official at-large delegates,
leaving open the possibility of two Georgia delegations showing up
in New Orleans.
   Thirty other GOP delegates were already picked at district
conventions.
   Stuckey had presided Friday over an abbreviated session marked
by chanting and booing by many of the 968 delegates _ mostly Pat
Robertson supporters and newcomers to party politics _ who had been
disqualified by the party regulars' credentials committee.
   The credentials committee, complying with a court order,
considered and granted appeals by many of the disqualified
delegates Friday evening and, on Saturday, party officials began
the lengthy process of registering the official delegates.
   But Stuckey adjourned the convention, saying it had been taken
over by what he described as an unruly mob. After leaving the
platform, he told reporters the court rulings would be appealed to
the state's highest court and, if necessary, the U.S. Supreme Court.
   Carl Gillis, a national committeeman from Adrian, said the
party's national credentials committee may have to decide which
delegation to recognize.
   ``This will probably wind up in an awful mess,'' Gillis added.
   The general counsel for the national Republican Party said the
party's nine-member contest committee will hear from both sides and
report its findings to the party's credentials committee.
   ``These people have done this job before and they play this game
strictly by the book,'' said Roger Allen Moore of Boston.
</TEXT>
