<1ST_LINE>u a AM-MultipleKillings     05-22 0331</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Multiple Killings,0342</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sister-In-Law Of Simmons Wants Second Trial For 14 Deaths</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RUSSELLVILLE, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The American Civil Liberties Union
will hold talks Monday to try to find a way to override the wishes
of convicted mass-murderer R. Gene Simmons and halt his planned
execution, an official said.
   The ACLU is concerned that Simmons could go from trial to
execution without a review by another court, a situation
unprecedented in recent U.S. judicial history, Jay Jacobson,
executive director of the ACLU's Arkansas chapter, said Saturday.
   The chapter's executive committee agreed Saturday to do
something about the Simmons case, but it remains unclear what
action the organization can take because it has no direct stake in
the case, Jacobson said.
   Typically, defendants or their close relatives appeal death
sentences.
   Potential actions range from issuing a statement expressing
disappointment at a lack of mandatory review to ``filing some sort
of litigation,'' Jacobson said.
   Simmons was scheduled last week to die by injection on June 27
for the Dec. 28 murders of Kathy Kendrick and David Chaffin during
a 45-minute shooting rampage in Russellville.
   He has said no one should try to halt the execution, which he
described as correct punishment for his conviction for capital
murder.
   Simmons also is scheduled to stand trial July 18 for the
Christmas holiday shooting and strangulation deaths of his wife,
Rebecca, and 13 other members of his family.
   Survivors of the family members want Simmons tried for their
deaths before he is executed for the two other slayings, Simmons'
sister-in-law said.
   Edith Nesby, sister of Rebecca Simmons, was quoted in the
Russellville Courier Democrat Saturday as saying she and other
survivors ``still cry for justice.''
   ``They can't put him to death three times, that's true, but when
he does go to death, we want him to go to death for all the
deaths,'' she was quoted as saying from Briggsdale, Colo., where
the cremated remains of Mrs. Simmons and four of her children are
buried.
</TEXT>
