<2ND_LINE>AM-Peru, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0867,0826</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>PRECEDE: Lima</HEAD>
<HEAD>President Garcia Says Probe Of Peasant Killings To Continue</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 8 grafs to UPDATE with President Garcia's surprise
visit to town, says probe to continue. Pickup 3rd graf pvs ``A
communique...''; SUBS 11th graf ``Carlos Enrique...'' with one graf
to CONFORM; EDITS thereafter to TRIM</NOTE>
<DATELINE>AYACUCHO, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Alan Garcia paid a surprise
visit Sunday to an Andean town where residents say troops killed
dozens of people in retaliation for the guerrilla ambush of a
military convoy.
   ``Democracy at times may make mistakes but its biggest mistake
would be to hide anything,'' Garcia told reporters in Ayacucho.
   While a government communique earlier Sunday said a ministerial
commission denied reports of the killings, Garcia and a later
government statement said an investigation will continue.
   Ayacucho's district attorney said troops killed at least 20
peasants on May 14 in the town of Cayara, 30 miles south of the
provincial capital, and that soldiers were not cooperating with his
investigation. A congressional investigative commission said at
least 30 were slain.
   Garcia flew to Cayara in a military helicopter from Ayacucho,
where he was attending a meeting of youth leaders of his
center-left Aprista Party. He said he spoke with residents and
officials in Cayara.
   Garcia also met with Carlos Enrique Escobar, the state's
district attorney. ``I know that yesterday was a visit by a
ministerial commission, but I would also like to listen to the
point of view of Dr. Escobar, who has had some preoccupations that
must be clarified,'' Garcia told reporters. ``My suggestion will be
that the commission that was here yesterday return accompanied with
Dr. Escobar.''
   Garcia, protected by heavy security, said the investigation
should continue in order to clarify exactly how many people died
and their cause of death.
   A communique signed by Prime Minister Armando Villanueva in
Lima, the nation's capital, said a government investigative
commission visited the town Saturday and found no evidence of a
massacre.
   The statement said testimony from villagers proved the
``falsehood of reports of rapes of women, house-burnings,
bombardments, assassination of children, a hundred deaths and other
acts of genocide.''
   But in a second communique issued Sunday night, the Lima
government said testimony gathered from townspeople indicated
``unclarified armed acts'' took place in the village and said the
investigation would continue.
   The government said it was ordering the military command in
Ayacucho, high in the Andes 230 miles southeast of Lima, to
cooperate fully with the investigation being conducted by the
district attorney's office.
   The government commission was composed of Defense Minister Gen.
Enrique Lopez Albujar, Justice Minister Camilo Carrillo, Raul
Ferrero Costa, president of the Lima Law Association, and Monsignor
Augusto Beuzeville Ferro, assistant bishop of Lima.
   Survivors of the alleged massacre made a formal denunciation
Thursday of an attack by army troops May 14 against Cayara, a town
of 1,500 people.
   The survivors said in a statement that army troops killed 47 men
between the ages of 15 and 62, including eight high school
students, their principal, the town's justice of peace and the
Cayara prefect, a position with duties similar to those of a police
chief.
   The statement said 51 other people were missing, including women
who had been raped by troops.
   Escobar said he visited Cayara Saturday with a coroner and his
assistants and had seen at least four burned homes. He said that
based on interviews with survivors he determined at least 20
villagers were killed by troops.
   Escobar said troops guarding the entrance to Cayara would not
let the autopsy team enter the town and would not give him
permission to dig up an area where survivors said dozens of victims
had been buried by troops.
   The four members of a congressional team also returned to
Ayacucho Sunday after visiting Cayara and told reporters they found
evidence of the slaying of at least 30 non-combatants.
   Gen. Cesar Valdivia, military commander of the Ayacucho region,
told reporters some 200 guerrillas had ambushed an army patrol two
miles outside Cayara the day before the alleged massacre.
   ``It is evident that a good proportion of the personnel that
participated in the ambush comes from the community of Cayara
because it is considered controlled by the terrorists,'' he said.
   The impoverished highlands surrounding this provincial capital
were the birthplace of the Shining Path insurgency eight years ago
this month and remain the stronghold of the Maoist guerrillas.
   The area has been under military control since late 1982.
   More than 10,000 people have been killed in the violence since
1980, most of them highland peasants caught in the crossfire
between guerrillas and security forces.
   In the two largest massacres on record, the Shining Path is
blamed for the slaughter of 83 peasants in 1983 and army troops for
the slaying of 69 villagers in 1985.
</TEXT>
