<HEAD>Prisoner Takes Guards Hostage, Escapes</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with four grafs to UPDATE with authorities saying woman
in car was inmate's wife. Picks up 5th graf pvs ``Apparently, they
...''</NOTE>
<DATELINE>CHILLICOTHE, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An inmate took two guards hostage
Sunday night and then escaped in a prison jeep, briefly taking the
guards with him before meeting his wife in a getaway car,
authorities said.
   Michael Day, who was serving a sentence of 18 to 55 years at the
medium-security Ross Correctional Institution, left the guards at a
hotel then fled in a car with his wife and a child, said Todd
Bennett, a dispatcher at the State Highway Patrol's Chillicothe
post.
   Day, 31, was believed armed with a .25-caliber automatic gun,
Bennett said.
   Day apparently was assisted in the escape by his wife, Sylvia
Caraveo Day, 27, Bennett said. They were accompanied by a
9-year-old child, but the patrol did not know whether the child was
related to the Days.
   ``Apparently, they were in on it somehow,'' he said. ``They
picked him up somewhere.''
   Prison spokeswoman Sandy Price said the two guards were not
injured and were being questioned by patrol officials and prison
Superintendent Gary Mohr.
   Neither Price nor Bennett could say how Day took the guards
hostage or managed to escape.
   Day was convicted of attempted abduction, burglary, receiving
stolen property and carrying a concealed weapon after a felony
conviction, Ms. Price said. He had been at the Ross prison in this
southern Ohio city 50 miles south of Columbus since June 1987, she
said.
   He had served time at the Chillicothe Correctional Institute and
Ohio State Reformatory in Mansfield since April 1985, Ms. Price
said.
