<1ST_LINE>d f AM-Iran-OPEC     05-22 0246</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iran-OPEC,0255</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iran Campaigns for Reduction of Oil Production</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MUSCAT, Oman (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iranian Oil Minister Gholamreza Aqazadeh
arrived here Sunday, apparently to garner support for an oil
production cut in advance of June's meeting of the ministerial
council of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries.
   Aqazadeh, who also will visit the United Arab Emirates and
Indonesia, said Iran supported the proposal for an all-round cut in
output by oil producers from within and outside the 13-nation
international cartel.
   He also told Omani reporters that joint cuts ``could constitute
the nucleus for strong cooperation'' between the two blocs.
   Following his talks with his Omani counterpart, Ahmed Saeed
Al-Shanfari, the Omani news agency said talks dealt with the world
market situation and the outcome of last month's oil talks in
Vienna, Austria in quest of stabilizing world oil prices. But it
did not elaborate.
   Oman last month joined five other non-OPEC nations in offering a
5 percent cut in output provided OPEC also reduced its production
ceiling by an equal proportion. At a subsequent meeting in Vienna,
OPEC members could not agree on the proposal and further
discussions were deferred to the cartel's semi-annual meeting
starting June 8 in Vienna.
   Key opponents of the plan were Saudi Arabia and Kuwait.
   Oman, which has cooperated with OPEC over the past two years in
reducing its output to help stabilize flagging oil prices, has
reversed the cuts temporarily and until the June meeting, according
to oil industry sources.
</TEXT>
